# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: raylib
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies, such as typography, cartography, technical drawing, advertising, etc.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] In many domains, such as desktop publishing, engineering, and business, a description of a document based on 2D computer graphics techniques can be much smaller than the corresponding digital image—often by a factor of 1/1000 or more.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] This representation is also more flexible since it can be rendered at different resolutions to suit different output devices.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, documents and illustrations are often stored or transmitted as 2D graphic files.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] 2D computer graphics started in the 1950s, based on vector graphics devices.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] These were largely supplanted by raster-based devices in the following decades.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The PostScript language and the X Window System protocol were landmark developments in the field.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics models may combine geometric models (also called vector graphics), digital images (also called raster graphics), text to be typeset (defined by content, font style and size, color, position, and orientation), mathematical functions and equations, and more.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] These components can be modified and manipulated by two-dimensional geometric transformations such as translation, rotation, and scaling.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] In object-oriented graphics, the image is described indirectly by an object endowed with a self-rendering method—a procedure that assigns colors to the image pixels by an arbitrary algorithm.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Complex models can be built by combining simpler objects, in the paradigms of object-oriented programming.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] In Euclidean geometry, a *translation (geometry)* moves every point a constant distance in a specified direction.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can be described as a rigid motion: other rigid motions include rotations and reflections.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] A translation can also be interpreted as the addition of a constant vector to every point, or as shifting the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] If *T* is a translation, then the image of a subset *A* under the function *T* is the **translation** of *A* by *T*.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The translation of *A* by *T***v** is often written *A* + **v**.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] In a Euclidean space, any translation is an isometry.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all translations forms the translation group *T*, which is isomorphic to the space itself, and a normal subgroup of Euclidean group *E*(*n* ).
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Since a translation is an affine transformation but not a linear transformation, homogeneous coordinates are normally used to represent the translation operator by a matrix and thus to make it linear.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Because addition of vectors is commutative, multiplication of translation matrices is therefore also commutative (unlike multiplication of arbitrary matrices).
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] In linear algebra, a *rotation matrix* is a matrix that is used to perform a rotation in Euclidean space.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] rotates points in the *xy*-Cartesian plane counterclockwise through an angle *θ* about the origin of the Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] To perform the rotation using a rotation matrix *R*, the position of each point must be represented by a column vector **v**, containing the coordinates of the point.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] A rotated vector is obtained by using the matrix multiplication *R***v**.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Since matrix multiplication has no effect on the zero vector (i.e., on the coordinates of the origin), rotation matrices can only be used to describe rotations about the origin of the coordinate system.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices provide a simple algebraic description of such rotations, and are used extensively for computations in geometry, physics, and computer graphics.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] In 2-dimensional space, a rotation can be simply described by an angle *θ* of rotation, but it can be also represented by the 4 entries of a rotation matrix with 2 rows and 2 columns.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] In 3-dimensional space, every rotation can be interpreted as a rotation by a given angle about a single fixed axis of rotation (see Euler's rotation theorem), and hence it can be simply described by an angle and a vector with 3 entries.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] However, it can also be represented by the 9 entries of a rotation matrix with 3 rows and 3 columns.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The notion of rotation is not commonly used in dimensions higher than 3; there is a notion of a *rotational displacement*, which can be represented by a matrix, but no associated single axis or angle.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Rotation matrices are square matrices, with real entries.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The set of all such matrices of size *n* forms a group, known as the special orthogonal group SO(*n*).
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] A convenient way to create a complex image is to start with a blank "canvas" raster map (an array of pixels, also known as a bitmap) filled with some uniform background color and then "draw", "paint" or "paste" simple patches of color onto it, in an appropriate order.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] In particular the canvas may be the frame buffer for a computer display.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Text, shapes and lines are rendered with a client-specified color.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Many libraries and cards provide color gradients, which are handy for the generation of smoothly-varying backgrounds, shadow effects, etc.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The pixel colors can also be taken from a texture, e.g. a digital image (thus emulating rub-on screentones and the fabled *checker paint* which used to be available only in cartoons).
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Painting a pixel with a given color usually replaces its previous color.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] However, many systems support painting with transparent and translucent colors, which only modify the previous pixel values.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The two colors may also be combined in more complex ways, e.g. by computing their bitwise exclusive or.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] This technique is known as *inverting color* or *color inversion*, and is often used in graphical user interfaces for highlighting, rubber-band drawing, and other volatile painting—since re-painting the same shapes with the same color will restore the original pixel values.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The models used in 2D computer graphics usually do not provide for three-dimensional shapes, or three-dimensional optical phenomena such as lighting, shadows, reflection, refraction, etc.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] However, they usually can model multiple *layers* (conceptually of ink, paper, or film; opaque, translucent, or transparent—stacked in a specific order.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The ordering is usually defined by a single number (the layer's *depth*, or distance from the viewer).
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are sometimes called "21⁄2-D computer graphics".
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] They make it possible to mimic traditional drafting and printing techniques based on film and paper, such as cutting and pasting; and allow the user to edit any layer without affecting the others.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] For these reasons, they are used in most graphics editors.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models also allow better spatial anti-aliasing of complex drawings and provide a sound model for certain techniques such as *mitered joints* and the even–odd rule.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Layered models are also used to allow the user to suppress unwanted information when viewing or printing a document, e.g. roads or railways from a map, certain process layers from an integrated circuit diagram, or hand annotations from a business letter.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] In a layer-based model, the target image is produced by "painting" or "pasting" each layer, in order of decreasing depth, on the virtual canvas.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Conceptually, each layer is first rendered on its own, yielding a digital image with the desired resolution which is then painted over the canvas, pixel by pixel.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Fully transparent parts of a layer need not be rendered, of course.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The rendering and painting may be done in parallel, i.e., each layer pixel may be painted on the canvas as soon as it is produced by the rendering procedure.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Layers that consist of complex geometric objects (such as text or polylines) may be broken down into simpler elements (characters or line segments, respectively), which are then painted as separate layers, in some order.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] However, this solution may create undesirable aliasing artifacts wherever two elements overlap the same pixel.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] See also Portable Document Format#Layers.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Modern computer graphics card displays almost overwhelmingly use raster techniques, dividing the screen into a rectangular grid of pixels, due to the relatively low cost of raster-based video hardware as compared with vector graphic hardware.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Most graphic hardware has internal support for blitting operations or sprite drawing.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] A co-processor dedicated to blitting is known as a *Blitter chip*.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Many graphical user interfaces (GUIs), including macOS, Microsoft Windows, or the X Window System, are primarily based on 2D graphical concepts.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Such software provides a visual environment for interacting with the computer, and commonly includes some form of window manager to aid the user in conceptually distinguishing between different applications.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The user interface within individual software applications is typically 2D in nature as well, due in part to the fact that most common input devices, such as the mouse, are constrained to two dimensions of movement.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics are very important in the control peripherals such as printers, plotters, sheet cutting machines, etc.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] They were also used in most early video games; and are still used for card and board games such as solitaire, chess, mahjongg, etc.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] 2D graphics editors or *drawing programs* are application-level software for the creation of images, diagrams and illustrations by direct manipulation (through the mouse, graphics tablet, or similar device) of 2D computer graphics primitives.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally provide geometric primitives as well as digital images; and some even support procedural models.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The illustration is usually represented internally as a layered model, often with a hierarchical structure to make editing more convenient.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] These editors generally output graphics files where the layers and primitives are separately preserved in their original form.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] MacDraw, introduced in 1984 with the Macintosh line of computers, was an early example of this class; recent examples are the commercial products Adobe Illustrator and CorelDRAW, and the free editors such as xfig or Inkscape.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] There are also many 2D graphics editors specialized for certain types of drawings such as electrical, electronic and VLSI diagrams, topographic maps, computer fonts, etc.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Image editors are specialized for the manipulation of digital images, mainly by means of free-hand drawing/painting and signal processing operations.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] They typically use a direct-painting paradigm, where the user controls virtual pens, brushes, and other free-hand artistic instruments to apply paint to a virtual canvas.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Some image editors support a multiple-layer model; however, in order to support signal-processing operations like blurring each layer is normally represented as a digital image.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Therefore, any geometric primitives that are provided by the editor are immediately converted to pixels and painted onto the canvas.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] The name *raster graphics editor* is sometimes used to contrast this approach to that of general editors which also handle *vector graphics*.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] One of the first popular image editors was Apple's MacPaint, companion to MacDraw.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Modern examples are the free GIMP editor, and the commercial products Photoshop and Paint Shop Pro.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] This class too includes many specialized editors—for medicine, remote sensing, digital photography, etc.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] With the resurgence of 2D animation, free and proprietary software packages have become widely available for amateurs and professional animators.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] With software like RETAS UbiArt Framework and Adobe After Effects, coloring and compositing can be done in less time.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Various approaches have been developed to aid and speed up the process of digital 2D animation.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] For example, by generating vector artwork in a tool like Adobe Flash an artist may employ software-driven automatic coloring and in-betweening.
[src:raylib/2d-computer-graphics] Programs like Blender or Adobe Substance allow the user to do either 3D animation, 2D animation or combine both in its software allowing experimentation with multiple forms of animation.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C was initially developed as a successor to the B programming language at Bell Labs by Ritchie between 1972 and 1973.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Its initial purpose was to construct utilities running on Unix, and was later applied to re-implementing the kernel of the Unix operating system.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] During the 1980s, C gradually gained popularity, leading to it becoming one of the most widely used programming languages, with C compilers available for practically all modern computer architectures and operating systems.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The book *The C Programming Language*, co-authored by the original language designer, served for many years as the *de facto* standard for the language.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C has been standardized since 1989 by the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) and, subsequently, jointly by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC).
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C is an imperative procedural language, supporting structured programming, lexical variable scope, and recursion, with a static type system.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] It was designed to be compiled to provide low-level access to memory and language constructs that map efficiently to machine instructions, all with minimal runtime support.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Despite its low-level capabilities, the language was designed to encourage cross-platform programming.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] A standards-compliant C program written with portability in mind can be compiled for a wide variety of computer platforms and operating systems with few changes to its source code.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Although neither C nor its standard library provide some popular features found in other languages, it is flexible enough to support them.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] For example, object orientation and garbage collection are provided by external libraries GLib Object System and Boehm garbage collector, respectively.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Since 2000, C has typically ranked as the most or second-most popular language in the TIOBE index.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C is an imperative, procedural language with a free-form source layout.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Statements are terminated by semicolons and grouped into blocks using curly braces.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] All executable code is contained in functions rather than top-level statements.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The language has a relatively small number of keywords, and user-defined identifiers are not distinguished from keywords by any sigil.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Parameters are passed by value; pass-by-reference is achieved with pointers.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] A function's return value may be ignored, and while a function cannot normally be nested inside another function, some translators support this.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C supports recursion, and run-time polymorphism may be achieved using function pointers.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Control flow is provided through constructs such as `if`, `for`, `do`, `while`, and `switch`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The language offers arithmetic; bitwise; and logical operators including `+`, `+=`, `++`, `&`, `||`, and multiple assignments may be performed in a single statement.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] A variable declared inside a block is accessible only within that block and only below its declaration.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Data typing is weakly enforced and static, with implicit conversion between primitive types.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] User-defined types allow aliasing of type specifiers.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Arrays are defined and accessed with square-bracket notation, for example `month[11]`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] User-defined structure types let related data elements be passed and copied as a unit, though two structures cannot be compared without custom code to compare each field.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Unions support overlapping members, allowing multiple data types to share the same memory location, and enumeration types support aliasing integer values.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C lacks a dedicated string type but provides syntax for null-terminated strings, with associated handling in its standard library.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The language supports low-level access to computer memory via pointers, procedure-like constructs in the form of functions returning `void`, and dynamic memory allocation through standard library functions.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] It includes the C preprocessor for macro definition, source-file inclusion, and conditional compilation.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Modularity is supported by processing files separately, with visibility controlled through the `static` and `extern` attributes.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Functionality is minimized in the core language, with relatively complex features such as I/O, string manipulation, and mathematical functions being provided through standard libraries.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The resulting compiled code has relatively straightforward requirements of the underlying platform, making C desirable for operating and embedded systems.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The "Hello, World!" program example that appeared in the first edition of *K&R* has become the model for an introductory program in most programming textbooks.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The program prints "hello, world" to the standard output.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The first line is a preprocessor directive, indicated by `#include`, which causes the preprocessor to replace that line of code with the text of the `stdio.h` header file, which contains declarations for input and output functions including `printf`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The angle brackets around `stdio.h` indicate that the header file can be located using a search strategy that selects header files provided with the compiler over files with the same name that may be found in project-specific directories.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The next code line declares the entry point function `main`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The run-time environment calls this function to begin program execution.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The type specifier `int` indicates that the function returns an integer value.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The `void` parameter list indicates that the function consumes no arguments.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The run-time environment actually passes two arguments (typed `int` and `char *[]`), but this implementation ignores them.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The ISO C standard (section 5.1.2.2.1) requires syntax that either is void or these two arguments – a special treatment not afforded to other functions.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The opening curly brace indicates the beginning of the code that defines the function.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The next line of code calls (diverts execution to) the C standard library function `printf` with the address of the first character of a null-terminated string specified as a string literal.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The text `\n` is an escape sequence that denotes the newline character which when output in a terminal results in moving the cursor to the beginning of the next line.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Even though `printf` returns an `int` value, it is silently discarded.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The semicolon `;` terminates the call statement.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The closing curly brace indicates the end of the `main` function.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Prior to C99, an explicit `return 0;` statement was required at the end of `main` function, but since C99, the `main` function (as being the initial function call) implicitly returns `0` upon reaching its final closing curly brace.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The origin of C is closely tied to the development of the Unix operating system, originally implemented in assembly language on a PDP-7 by Dennis Ritchie and Ken Thompson, incorporating several ideas from colleagues.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Eventually, they decided to port the operating system to a PDP-11.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The original PDP-11 version of Unix was also developed in assembly language.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Thompson wanted a programming language for developing utilities for the new platform.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] He first tried writing a Fortran compiler, but he soon gave up the idea and instead created a cut-down version of the recently developed systems programming language called BCPL.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The official description of BCPL was not available at the time, and Thompson modified the syntax to be less 'wordy' and similar to a simplified ALGOL known as SMALGOL.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] He called the result *B*, describing it as "BCPL semantics with a lot of SMALGOL syntax".
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Like BCPL, B had a bootstrapping compiler to facilitate porting to new machines.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Ultimately, few utilities were written in B because it was too slow and could not take advantage of PDP-11 features such as byte addressability.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Unlike BCPL's `// comment` marking comments up to the end of the line, B adopted `/* comment */` as the comment delimiter, more akin to PL/1, and allowing comments to appear in the middle of lines.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In 1971, Ritchie started to improve B, to use the features of the more-powerful PDP-11.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] A significant addition was a character data type.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Thompson started to use NB to write the Unix kernel, and his requirements shaped the direction of the language development.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Through to 1972, richer types were added to the NB language.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] NB had arrays of `int` and `char`, and to these types were added pointers, the ability to generate pointers to other types, arrays of all types, and types to be returned from functions.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Arrays within expressions were effectively treated as pointers.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] A new compiler was written, and the language was renamed C.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The C compiler and some utilities made with it were included in Version 2 Unix, which is also known as Research Unix.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] At Version 4 Unix, released in November 1973, the Unix kernel was extensively re-implemented in C.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] By this time, the C language had acquired some powerful features such as `struct` types.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The preprocessor was introduced around 1973 at the urging of Alan Snyder and also in recognition of the usefulness of the file-inclusion mechanisms available in BCPL and PL/I.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Its original version provided only included files and simple string replacements: `#include` and `#define` of parameterless macros.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Soon after that, it was extended, mostly by Mike Lesk and then by John Reiser, to incorporate macros with arguments and conditional compilation.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Unix was one of the first operating system kernels implemented in a language other than assembly.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Earlier instances include the Multics system (which was written in PL/I) and Master Control Program (MCP) for the Burroughs B5000 (which was written in ALGOL) in 1961.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In and around 1977, Ritchie and Stephen C.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Johnson made further changes to the language to facilitate portability of the Unix operating system.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Johnson's Portable C Compiler served as the basis for several implementations of C on new platforms.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In 1978, Brian Kernighan and Dennis Ritchie published the first edition of *The C Programming Language*.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Known as *K&R* from the initials of its authors, the book served for many years as an informal specification of the language.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The version of C that it describes is commonly referred to as "**K&R C**".
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] As this was released in 1978, it is now also referred to as *C78*.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The second edition of the book covers the later ANSI C standard, described below.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Although later versions of C require functions to have an explicit type declaration, K&R C only requires functions that return a type other than `int` to be declared before use.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Functions used without prior declaration were presumed to return `int`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The declaration of `long_function()` (on line 1) is required since it returns `long`; not `int`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Function `int_function` can be called (line 11) even though it is not declared since it returns `int`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Also, variable `intvar` does not need to be declared as type `int` since that is the default type for `register` keyword.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Since function declarations did not include information about arguments, type checks were not performed, although some compilers would issue a warning if different calls to a function used different numbers or types of arguments.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Tools such as Unix's lint utility were developed that (among other things) checked for consistency of function use across multiple source files.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In the years following the publication of K&R C, several features were added to the language, supported by compilers from AT&T (in particular PCC) and other vendors.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The popularity of the language, lack of agreement on standard library interfaces, and lack of compliance to the K&R specification, led to standardization efforts.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] During the late 1970s and 1980s, versions of C were implemented for a wide variety of mainframe computers, minicomputers, and microcomputers, including the IBM PC, as its popularity increased significantly.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In 1983 the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) formed a committee, X3J11, to establish a standard specification of C.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] X3J11 based the C standard on the Unix implementation; however, the non-portable portion of the Unix C library was handed off to the IEEE working group 1003 to become the basis for the 1988 POSIX standard.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In 1989, the C standard was ratified as ANSI X3.159-1989 "Programming Language C".
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] This version of the language is often referred to as ANSI C, Standard C, or sometimes **C89**.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In 1990 the ANSI C standard (with formatting changes) was adopted by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) as ISO/IEC 9899:1990, which is sometimes called **C90**.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Therefore, the terms "C89" and "C90" refer to the same programming language.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] ANSI, like other national standards bodies, no longer develops the C standard independently, but defers to the international C standard, maintained by the working group ISO/IEC JTC1/SC22/WG14.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] National adoption of an update to the international standard typically occurs within a year of ISO publication.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] One of the aims of the C standardization process was to produce a superset of K&R C, incorporating many of the subsequently introduced unofficial features.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The standards committee also included several additional features such as function prototypes (borrowed from C++), `void` pointers, support for international character sets and locales, and preprocessor enhancements.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Although the syntax for parameter declarations was augmented to include the style used in C++, the K&R interface continued to be permitted, for compatibility with existing source code.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C89 is supported by current C compilers, and most modern C code is based on it.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Any program written only in Standard C and without any hardware-dependent assumptions will run correctly on any platform with a conforming C implementation, within its resource limits.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In cases where code must be compilable by either standard-conforming or K&R C-based compilers, the `__STDC__` macro can be used to split the code into Standard and K&R sections to prevent the use on a K&R C-based compiler of features available only in Standard C.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] After the ANSI/ISO standardization process, the C language specification remained relatively static for several years.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In 1995, Normative Amendment 1 to the 1990 C standard (ISO/IEC 9899/AMD1:1995, known informally as C95) was published, to correct some details and to add more extensive support for international character sets.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The C standard was further revised in the late 1990s, leading to the publication of ISO/IEC 9899:1999 in 1999, which is commonly referred to as "C99".
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] It has since been amended three times by Technical Corrigenda.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Many of these had already been implemented as extensions in several C compilers.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C99 is for the most part backward compatible with C90, but is stricter in some ways; in particular, a declaration that lacks a type specifier no longer has `int` implicitly assumed.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] A standard macro `__STDC_VERSION__` is defined with value `199901L` to indicate that C99 support is available.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] GCC, Solaris Studio, and other C compilers now support many or all of the new features of C99.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The C compiler in Microsoft Visual C++, however, implements the C89 standard and those parts of C99 that are required for compatibility with C++11.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In addition, the C99 standard requires support for identifiers using Unicode in the form of escaped characters (e.g.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] `\u0040` or `\U0001f431`) and suggests support for raw Unicode names.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Work began in 2007 on another revision of the C standard, informally called "C1X" until its official publication of ISO/IEC 9899:2011 on December 8, 2011.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The C standards committee adopted guidelines to limit the adoption of new features that had not been tested by existing implementations.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The C11 standard adds numerous new features to C and the library, including type generic macros, anonymous structures, improved Unicode support, atomic operations, multi-threading, and bounds-checked functions.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] It also makes some portions of the existing C99 library optional, and improves compatibility with C++.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The standard macro `__STDC_VERSION__` is defined as `201112L` to indicate that C11 support is available.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C17 is an informal name for ISO/IEC 9899:2018, a standard for the C programming language published in June 2018.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] It introduces no new language features, only technical corrections, and clarifications to defects in C11.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The standard macro `__STDC_VERSION__` is defined as `201710L` to indicate that C17 support is available.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C23 is an informal name for the current major C language standard revision.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] It was known as "C2X" through most of its development.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] It builds on past releases, introducing features like new keywords, additional meaning for `auto` to provide type inference when declaring variables, new types including `nullptr_t` and `_BitInt(N)`, and expansions to the standard library.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The standard macro `__STDC_VERSION__` is defined as `202311L` to indicate that C23 support is available.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C2Y is an informal name for the next major C language standard revision, after C23 (C2X), that is hoped to be released later in the 2020s, hence the '2' in "C2Y".
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] An early working draft of C2Y was released in February 2024 as N3220 by the working group ISO/IEC JTC1/SC22/WG14.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Historically, embedded C programming requires non-standard extensions to the C language to support exotic features such as fixed-point arithmetic, multiple distinct memory banks, and basic I/O operations.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In 2008, the C Standards Committee published a technical report extending the C language to address these issues by providing a common standard for all implementations to adhere to.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] It includes a number of features not available in normal C, such as fixed-point arithmetic, named address spaces, and basic I/O hardware addressing.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C has a formal grammar specified by the C standard.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Line endings are generally not significant in C; however, line boundaries do have significance during the preprocessing phase.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Comments may appear either between the delimiters `/*` and `*/`, or (since C99) following `//` until the end of the line.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Comments delimited by `/*` and `*/` do not nest, and these sequences of characters are not interpreted as comment delimiters if they appear inside string or character literals.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C source files contain declarations and function definitions.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Function definitions, in turn, contain declarations and statements.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Declarations either define new types using keywords such as `struct`, `union`, and `enum`, or assign types to and perhaps reserve storage for new variables, usually by writing the type followed by the variable name.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Keywords such as `char` and `int` specify built-in types.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Sections of code are enclosed in braces (`{` and `}`, sometimes called "curly brackets") to limit the scope of declarations and to act as a single statement for control structures.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] As an imperative language, C uses *statements* to specify actions.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The most common statement is an *expression statement*, consisting of an expression to be evaluated, followed by a semicolon; as a side effect of the evaluation, functions may be called and variables assigned new values.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] To modify the normal sequential execution of statements, C provides several control-flow statements identified by reserved keywords.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Structured programming is supported by `if` ... [`else`] conditional execution and by `do` ...
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] `while`, `while`, and `for` iterative execution (looping).
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The `for` statement has separate initialization, testing, and reinitialization expressions, any or all of which can be omitted.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] `break` and `continue` can be used within the loop.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Break is used to leave the innermost enclosing loop statement and continue is used to skip to its reinitialisation.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] There is also a non-structured `goto` statement, which branches directly to the designated label within the function.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] `switch` selects a `case` to be executed based on the value of an integer expression.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Different from many other languages, control-flow will fall through to the next `case` unless terminated by a `break`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Expressions can use a variety of built-in operators and may contain function calls.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The order in which arguments to functions and operands to most operators are evaluated is unspecified.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The evaluations may even be interleaved.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] However, all side effects (including storage to variables) will occur before the next "sequence point"; sequence points include the end of each expression statement, and the entry to and return from each function call.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Sequence points also occur during evaluation of expressions containing certain operators (`&&`, `||`, `?:` and the comma operator).
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] This permits a high degree of object code optimization by the compiler, but requires C programmers to take more care to obtain reliable results than is needed for other programming languages.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Kernighan and Ritchie say in the Introduction of *The C Programming Language*: "C, like any other language, has its blemishes.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Some of the operators have the wrong precedence; some parts of the syntax could be better." The C standard did not attempt to correct many of these blemishes, because of the impact of such changes on already existing software.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The *newline* character indicates the end of a text line; it need not correspond to an actual single character, although for convenience C treats it as such.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The POSIX standard mandates a portable character set which adds a few characters (notably "@") to the basic C source character set.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Both standards do not prescribe any particular value encoding—ASCII and EBCDIC both comply with these standards, since they include at least those basic characters, even though they use different encoded values for those characters.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Additional multi-byte encoded characters may be used in string literals, but they are not entirely portable.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Since C99 multi-national Unicode characters can be embedded portably within C source text by using `\uXXXX` or `\UXXXXXXXX` encoding (where `X` denotes a hexadecimal character).
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The basic C execution character set contains the same characters, along with representations for the null character, alert, backspace, and carriage return.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Run-time support for extended character sets has increased with each revision of the C standard.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] All versions of C have reserved words that are case sensitive.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] As reserved words, they cannot be used for variable names.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Most of the recently reserved words begin with an underscore followed by a capital letter, because identifiers of that form were previously reserved by the C standard for use only by implementations.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Since existing program source code should not have been using these identifiers, it would not be affected when C implementations started supporting these extensions to the programming language.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Some standard headers do define more convenient synonyms for underscored identifiers.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Some of those words were added as keywords with their conventional spelling in C23 and the corresponding macros were removed.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Prior to C89, `entry` was reserved as a keyword.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C supports a rich set of operators, which are symbols used within an expression to specify the manipulations to be performed while evaluating that expression.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C uses the operator `=` (used in mathematics to express equality) to indicate assignment, following the precedent of Fortran and PL/I, but unlike ALGOL and its derivatives.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C uses the operator `==` to test for equality.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The similarity between the operators for assignment and equality may result in the accidental use of one in place of the other, and in many cases the mistake does not produce an error message (although some compilers produce warnings).
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] For example, the conditional expression `if (a == b + 1)` might mistakenly be written as `if (a = b + 1)`, which will be evaluated as `true` unless the value of `a` is `0` after the assignment.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The C operator precedence is not always intuitive.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] For example, the operator `==` binds more tightly than (is executed prior to) the operators `&` (bitwise AND) and `|` (bitwise OR) in expressions such as `x & 1 == 0`, which must be written as `(x & 1) == 0` if that is the coder's intent.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The type system in C is static and weakly typed, which makes it similar to the type system of ALGOL descendants such as Pascal.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] There are built-in types for integers of various sizes, both signed and unsigned, floating-point numbers, and enumerated types (`enum`).
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Integer type `char` is often used for single-byte characters.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] There are also derived types including arrays, pointers, records (`struct`), and unions (`union`).
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C is often used in low-level systems programming where escapes from the type system may be necessary.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Some find C's declaration syntax unintuitive, particularly for function pointers.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C's *usual arithmetic conversions* allow for efficient code to be generated, but can sometimes produce unexpected results.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] For example, a comparison of signed and unsigned integers of equal width requires a conversion of the signed value to unsigned.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] This can generate unexpected results if the signed value is negative.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C supports the use of pointers, a type of reference that records the address or location of an object or function in memory.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Pointers can be *dereferenced* to access data stored at the address pointed to, or to invoke a pointed-to function.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Pointers can be manipulated using assignment or pointer arithmetic.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The run-time representation of a pointer value is typically a raw memory address (perhaps augmented by an offset-within-word field), but since a pointer's type includes the type of the thing pointed to, expressions including pointers can be type-checked at compile time.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Pointer arithmetic is automatically scaled by the size of the pointed-to data type.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Pointers are used for many purposes in C.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Text strings are commonly manipulated using pointers into arrays of characters.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Dynamic memory allocation is performed using pointers; the result of a `malloc` is usually cast to the data type of the data to be stored.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Many data types, such as trees, are commonly implemented as dynamically allocated `struct` objects linked together using pointers.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Pointers to other pointers are often used in multi-dimensional arrays and arrays of `struct` objects.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Pointers to functions (*function pointers*) are useful for passing functions as arguments to higher-order functions (such as qsort or bsearch), in dispatch tables, or as callbacks to event handlers.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] A *null pointer value* explicitly points to no valid location.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Dereferencing a null pointer value is undefined, often resulting in a segmentation fault.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Null pointer values are useful for indicating special cases such as no "next" pointer in the final node of a linked list, or as an error indication from functions returning pointers.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In appropriate contexts in source code, such as for assigning to a pointer variable, a *null pointer constant* can be written as `0`, with or without explicit casting to a pointer type, as the `NULL` macro defined by several standard headers or, since C23 with the constant `nullptr`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In conditional contexts, null pointer values evaluate to `false`, while all other pointer values evaluate to `true`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Void pointers (`void *`) point to objects of unspecified type, and can therefore be used as "generic" data pointers.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Since the size and type of the pointed-to object is not known, void pointers cannot be dereferenced, nor is pointer arithmetic on them allowed, although they can easily be (and in many contexts implicitly are) converted to and from any other object pointer type.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Careless use of pointers is potentially dangerous.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Because they are typically unchecked, a pointer variable can be made to point to any arbitrary location, which can cause undesirable effects.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In general, C is permissive in allowing manipulation of and conversion between pointer types, although compilers typically provide options for various levels of checking.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Some other programming languages address these problems by using more restrictive reference types.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Array types in C are traditionally of a fixed, static size specified at compile time.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The more recent C99 standard also allows a form of variable-length arrays.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] However, it is also possible to allocate a block of memory (of arbitrary size) at run time, using the standard library's `malloc` function, and treat it as an array.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Since arrays are always accessed (in effect) via pointers, array accesses are typically not checked against the underlying array size, although some compilers may provide bounds checking as an option.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Array bounds violations are therefore possible and can lead to various repercussions, including illegal memory accesses, corruption of data, buffer overflows, and run-time exceptions.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] C does not have a special provision for declaring multi-dimensional arrays, but rather relies on recursion within the type system to declare arrays of arrays, which effectively accomplishes the same thing.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The index values of the resulting "multi-dimensional array" can be thought of as increasing in row-major order.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Multi-dimensional arrays are commonly used in numerical algorithms (mainly from applied linear algebra) to store matrices.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The structure of the C array is well suited to this particular task.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] However, in early versions of C the bounds of the array must be known fixed values or else explicitly passed to any subroutine that requires them, and dynamically sized arrays of arrays cannot be accessed using double indexing.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] (A workaround for this was to allocate the array with an additional "row vector" of pointers to the columns.) C99 introduced "variable-length arrays" which address this issue.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The subscript notation `x[i]` (where `x` designates a pointer) is syntactic sugar for `*(x+i)`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Taking advantage of the compiler's knowledge of the pointer type, the address that `x + i` points to is not the base address (pointed to by `x`) incremented by `i` bytes, but rather is defined to be the base address incremented by `i` multiplied by the size of an element that `x` points to.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Thus, `x[i]` designates the `i+1`th element of the array.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Furthermore, in most expression contexts (a notable exception is as operand of `sizeof`), an expression of array type is automatically converted to a pointer to the array's first element.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] This implies that an array is never copied as a whole when named as an argument to a function, but rather only the address of its first element is passed.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Therefore, although function calls in C use pass-by-value semantics, arrays are in effect passed by reference.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The total size of an array `x` can be determined by applying `sizeof` to an expression of array type.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The size of an element can be determined by applying the operator `sizeof` to any dereferenced element of an array `A`, as in `n = sizeof A[0]`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Thus, the number of elements in a declared array `A` can be determined as `sizeof A / sizeof A[0]`.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Note, that if only a pointer to the first element is available as it is often the case in C code because of the automatic conversion described above, the information about the full type of the array and its length are lost.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] One of the most important functions of a programming language is to provide facilities for managing memory and the objects that are stored in memory.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] These three approaches are appropriate in different situations and have various trade-offs.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] For example, static memory allocation has little allocation overhead, automatic allocation may involve slightly more overhead, and dynamic memory allocation can potentially have a great deal of overhead for both allocation and deallocation.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Most C programs make extensive use of all three.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Where possible, automatic or static allocation is usually simplest because the storage is managed by the compiler, freeing the programmer of the potentially error-prone chore of manually allocating and releasing storage.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] However, many data structures can change in size at run time, and since static allocations (and automatic allocations before C99) must have a fixed size at compile time, there are many situations in which dynamic allocation is necessary.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Prior to the C99 standard, variable-sized arrays were a common example of this.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Unless otherwise specified, static objects contain zero or null pointer values upon program startup.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Automatically and dynamically allocated objects are initialized only if an initial value is explicitly specified; otherwise they initially have indeterminate values (typically, whatever bit pattern happens to be present in the storage, which might not even represent a valid value for that type).
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] If the program attempts to access an uninitialized value, the results are undefined.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Many modern compilers try to detect and warn about this problem, but both false positives and false negatives can occur.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Heap memory allocation has to be synchronized with its actual usage in any program to be reused as much as possible.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] For example, if the only pointer to a heap memory allocation goes out of scope or has its value overwritten before it is deallocated explicitly, then that memory cannot be recovered for later reuse and is essentially lost to the program, a phenomenon known as a *memory leak*.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Conversely, it is possible for memory to be freed but referenced subsequently, leading to unpredictable results.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Typically, the failure symptoms appear in a portion of the program unrelated to the code that causes the error, making it difficult to diagnose the failure.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Such issues are ameliorated in languages with automatic garbage collection.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The C programming language uses libraries as its primary method of extension.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In C, a library is a set of functions contained within a single "archive" file.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Each library typically has a header file, which contains the prototypes of the functions contained within the library that may be used by a program, and declarations of special data types and macro symbols used with these functions.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] For a program to use a library, it must include the library's header file, and the library must be linked with the program, which in many cases requires compiler flags (e.g., `-lm`, shorthand for "link the math library").
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The most common C library is the C standard library, which is specified by the ISO and ANSI C standards and comes with every C implementation (implementations which target limited environments such as embedded systems may provide only a subset of the standard library).
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] This library supports stream input and output, memory allocation, mathematics, character strings, and time values.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Several separate standard headers (for example, `stdio.h`) specify the interfaces for these and other standard library facilities.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Another common set of C library functions are those used by applications specifically targeted for Unix and Unix-like systems, especially functions which provide an interface to the kernel.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] These functions are detailed in various standards such as POSIX and the Single UNIX Specification.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Since many programs have been written in C, there are a wide variety of other libraries available.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Libraries are often written in C because C compilers generate efficient object code; programmers then create interfaces to the library so that the routines can be used from higher-level languages like Java, Perl, and Python.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] File input and output (I/O) is not part of the C language itself but instead is handled by libraries (such as the C standard library) and their associated header files (e.g.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] File handling is generally implemented through high-level I/O which works through streams.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] A stream is from this perspective a data flow that is independent of devices, while a file is a concrete device.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] The high-level I/O is done through the association of a stream to a file.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] In the C standard library, a buffer (a memory area or queue) is temporarily used to store data before it is sent to the final destination.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] This reduces the time spent waiting for slower devices, for example a hard drive or solid-state drive.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Low-level I/O functions are not part of the standard C library but are generally part of "bare metal" programming (programming that is independent of any operating system such as most embedded programming).
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] With few exceptions, implementations include low-level I/O.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] A number of tools have been developed to help C programmers find and fix statements with undefined behavior or possibly erroneous expressions, with greater rigor than that provided by the compiler.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Automated source code checking and auditing tools exist, such as Lint.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] A common practice is to use Lint to detect questionable code when a program is first written.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Once a program passes Lint, it is then compiled using the C compiler.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Also, many compilers can optionally warn about syntactically valid constructs that are likely to actually be errors.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] MISRA C is a proprietary set of guidelines to avoid such questionable code, developed for embedded systems.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] There are also compilers, libraries, and operating system level mechanisms for performing actions that are not a standard part of C, such as bounds checking for arrays, detection of buffer overflow, serialization, dynamic memory tracking, and automatic garbage collection.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p01] Memory management checking tools like Purify or Valgrind and linking with libraries containing special versions of the memory allocation functions can help uncover run-time errors in memory usage.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] C has been widely used to implement end-user and system-level applications.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] C is widely used for systems programming in implementing operating systems and embedded system applications.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Computer games are often built from a combination of languages.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] C has featured significantly, especially for those games attempting to obtain best performance from computer platforms.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Historically, C was sometimes used for web development using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) as a "gateway" for information between the web application, the server, and the browser.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] C may have been chosen over interpreted languages because of its speed, stability, and near-universal availability.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] It is no longer common practice for web development to be done in C, and many other web development languages are popular.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Applications where C-based web development continues include the HTTP configuration pages on routers, IoT devices and similar, although even here some projects have parts in higher-level languages e.g. the use of Lua within OpenWRT.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Two popular web servers, Apache HTTP Server and Nginx, are written in C.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] C's close-to-the-metal approach allows for the construction of these high-performance software systems.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] C is sometimes used as an intermediate language by implementations of other languages.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] This approach may be used for portability or convenience; by using C as an intermediate language, additional machine-specific code generators are not necessary.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] C has some features, such as line-number preprocessor directives and optional superfluous commas at the end of initializer lists, that support compilation of generated code.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] However, some of C's shortcomings have prompted the development of other C-based languages specifically designed for use as intermediate languages, such as C--.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Also, contemporary major compilers GCC and LLVM both feature an intermediate representation that is not C, and those compilers support front ends for many languages including C.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] C enables programmers to create efficient implementations of algorithms and data structures, because the layer of abstraction from hardware is thin, and its overhead is low, an important criterion for computationally intensive programs.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] For example, the GNU Multiple Precision Arithmetic Library, the GNU Scientific Library, Mathematica, and MATLAB are completely or partially written in C.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Many languages support calling library functions in C; for example, the Python-based framework NumPy uses C for the high-performance and hardware-interacting aspects.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] A consequence of C's wide availability and efficiency is that compilers, libraries and interpreters of other programming languages are often implemented in C.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] For example, the reference implementations of Python, Perl, Ruby, and PHP are written in C.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] For some purposes, restricted styles of C have been adopted, e.g.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] MISRA C or CERT C, in an attempt to reduce the opportunity for unwanted behaviour.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Databases such as CWE attempt to count the ways that systems in general, especially those coded in C, have potential vulnerabilities, along with recommendations for mitigation.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] There are tools that can mitigate some of the drawbacks.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Contemporary C compilers include checks which may generate warnings to help identify many potential bugs.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] C's use of pointers can be made less risky by use of instruction set architecture extensions such as *CHERI* or *Permission Overlay Extensions*.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] These techniques change the fundamental nature of pointers at a hardware level to include bounds checks and purposes, which can help prevent buffer over-runs and inappropriate heap accesses.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Since the early 2020s the Linux kernel has sections written in Rust, a language which has specific measures to improve safety.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Many languages developed after C were influenced by and borrowed aspects of C, including C++, C#, C shell, D, Go, Java, JavaScript, Julia, Limbo, LPC, Objective-C, Perl, PHP, Python, Ruby, Rust, Swift, Verilog and SystemVerilog.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Some claim that the most pervasive influence has been syntactical – that these languages combine the statement and expression syntax of C with type systems, data models and large-scale program structures that differ from those of C, sometimes radically.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Several C or near-C interpreters exist, including Ch and CINT, which can also be used for scripting.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] When object-oriented programming languages became popular, C++ and Objective-C were two different extensions of C that provided object-oriented capabilities.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Both languages were originally implemented as source-to-source compilers; source code was translated into C, and then compiled with a C compiler.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] The C++ programming language (originally named "C with Classes") was devised by Bjarne Stroustrup as an approach to providing object-oriented functionality with a C-like syntax.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] C++ adds greater typing strength, scoping, and other tools useful in object-oriented programming, and permits generic programming via templates.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Nearly a superset of C, C++ now supports most of C, with a few exceptions.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Objective-C was originally a thin layer on top of C, and remains a strict superset of C that permits object-oriented programming using a hybrid dynamic/static typing paradigm.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] Objective-C derives its syntax from both C and Smalltalk: syntax that involves preprocessing, expressions, function declarations, and function calls is inherited from C, while the syntax for object-oriented features was originally taken from Smalltalk.
[src:raylib/c-programming-language-p02] In addition to C++ and Objective-C, Ch, Cilk, and Unified Parallel C are nearly supersets of C.
[src:raylib/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:raylib/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:raylib/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:raylib/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:raylib/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:raylib/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:raylib/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:raylib/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:raylib/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:raylib/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:raylib/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:raylib/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:raylib/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:raylib/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:raylib/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:raylib/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:raylib/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:raylib/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:raylib/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:raylib/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:raylib/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:raylib/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:raylib/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:raylib/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:raylib/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:raylib/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:raylib/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:raylib/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:raylib/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:raylib/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:raylib/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:raylib/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:raylib/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:raylib/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:raylib/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:raylib/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:raylib/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:raylib/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:raylib/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] without the use of extensive indirection – thus***immediate***– to retained resources.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] It does not preclude the use of double-buffering.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Retained mode is an alternative approach.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Historically, retained mode has been the dominant style in GUI libraries; however, both can coexist in the same library and are not necessarily exclusive in practice.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] In immediate mode, the scene (complete object model of the rendering primitives) is retained in the memory space of the client, instead of the graphics library.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This implies that in an immediate mode application, the lists of graphical objects to be rendered are kept by the client and are not saved by the graphics library API.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] The application must re-issue all drawing commands required to describe the entire scene each time a new frame is required, regardless of actual changes.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This method provides on the one hand a maximum of control and flexibility to the application program, but on the other hand it also generates continuous work load on the CPU.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Examples of immediate mode rendering systems include Direct2D, OpenGL and Quartz.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] There are some immediate mode GUIs that are particularly suitable when used in conjunction with immediate mode rendering systems.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Primitive vertex attribute data may be inserted frame by frame into a command buffer by a rendering API.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] This involves significant bandwidth and processor time (especially if the graphics processing unit is on a separate bus), but may be advantageous for data generated dynamically by the CPU.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] It is less common since the advent of increasingly versatile shaders, with which a graphics processing unit may generate increasingly complex effects without the need for CPU intervention.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Graphical user interfaces traditionally use retained mode-style API design, but immediate mode GUIs instead use an immediate mode-style API design, in which user code directly specifies the GUI elements to draw in the user input loop.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] For example, rather than having a CreateButton() function that a user would call once to instantiate a button, an immediate-mode GUI API may have a DoButton() function which should be called whenever the button should be on screen.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] The technique was developed by Casey Muratori in 2002.
[src:raylib/immediate-mode-computer-graphics] Prominent implementations include Omar Cornut's Dear ImGui in C++, Nic Barker's Clay in C and Micha Mettke's Nuklear in C.
[src:raylib/opengl] (SGI) began developing OpenGL in 1991 and released it on June 30, 1992.
[src:raylib/opengl] It is used for a variety of applications, including computer-aided design (CAD), video games, scientific visualization, virtual reality, and flight simulation.
[src:raylib/opengl] Since 2006, OpenGL has been managed by the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group.
[src:raylib/opengl] The OpenGL specification describes an abstract application programming interface (API) for drawing 2D and 3D graphics.
[src:raylib/opengl] It is designed to be implemented mostly or entirely using hardware acceleration such as a GPU, although it is possible for the API to be implemented entirely in software running on a CPU.
[src:raylib/opengl] The API is defined as a set of functions which may be called by the client program, alongside a set of named integer constants (for example, the constant GL_TEXTURE_2D, which corresponds to the decimal number 3553).
[src:raylib/opengl] Although the function definitions are superficially similar to those of the programming language C, they are language-independent.
[src:raylib/opengl] As such, OpenGL has many language bindings, some of the most noteworthy being the JavaScript binding WebGL (API, based on OpenGL ES 2.0, for 3D rendering from within a web browser); the C bindings WGL, GLX and CGL; the C binding provided by iOS; and the Java and C bindings provided by Android.
[src:raylib/opengl] In addition to being language-independent, OpenGL is also cross-platform.
[src:raylib/opengl] The specification says nothing on the subject of obtaining and managing an OpenGL context, leaving this as a detail of the underlying windowing system.
[src:raylib/opengl] For the same reason, OpenGL is purely concerned with rendering, providing no APIs related to input, audio, or windowing.
[src:raylib/opengl] New versions of the OpenGL specifications are released by the Khronos Group, each of which extends the API to support various new features.
[src:raylib/opengl] The details of each version are decided by consensus between the Group's members, including graphics card manufacturers, operating system designers, and general technology companies such as Mozilla and Google.
[src:raylib/opengl] In addition to the features required by the core API, graphics processing unit (GPU) vendors may provide additional functionality in the form of *extensions*.
[src:raylib/opengl] Extensions may introduce new functions and new constants, and may relax or remove restrictions on existing OpenGL functions.
[src:raylib/opengl] Vendors can use extensions to expose custom APIs without needing support from other vendors or the Khronos Group as a whole, which greatly increases the flexibility of OpenGL.
[src:raylib/opengl] All extensions are collected in, and defined by, the OpenGL Registry.
[src:raylib/opengl] The features introduced by each new version of OpenGL are typically formed from the combined features of several widely implemented extensions, especially extensions of type ARB or EXT.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL is no longer in active development; whereas between 2001 and 2014, OpenGL specification was updated mostly on a yearly basis, with two releases (3.1 and 3.2) taking place in 2009 and three (3.3, 4.0 and 4.1) in 2010.
[src:raylib/opengl] The latest OpenGL specification 4.6 was released in 2017 after a three-year break, and was limited to inclusion of eleven existing ARB and EXT extensions into the core profile.
[src:raylib/opengl] Active development of OpenGL was dropped in favor of the Vulkan API, released in 2016, and codenamed glNext during initial development.
[src:raylib/opengl] In 2017, Khronos Group announced that OpenGL ES would not have new versions and has since concentrated on development of Vulkan and other technologies.
[src:raylib/opengl] As a result, certain capabilities offered by modern GPUs, e.g. ray tracing, are not supported by the OpenGL standard.
[src:raylib/opengl] However, support for newer features might be provided through the vendor-specific OpenGL extensions.
[src:raylib/opengl] The OpenGL Architecture Review Board released a series of manuals along with the specification which have been updated to track changes in the API.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL Programming for the X Window System.
[src:raylib/opengl] Includes a poster-sized fold-out diagram showing the structure of an idealised OpenGL implementation.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL Programming for Windows 95 and Windows NT.
[src:raylib/opengl] A book about interfacing OpenGL with Microsoft Windows.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL's documentation is also accessible via its official webpage.
[src:raylib/opengl] The earliest versions of OpenGL were released with a companion library called the OpenGL Utility Library (GLU).
[src:raylib/opengl] It provided simple, useful features which were unlikely to be supported in contemporary hardware, such as tessellating, and generating mipmaps and primitive shapes.
[src:raylib/opengl] The GLU specification was last updated in 1998 and depends on OpenGL features which are now deprecated.
[src:raylib/opengl] Given that creating an OpenGL context is quite a complex process, and given that it varies between operating systems, automatic OpenGL context creation has become a common feature of several game-development and user-interface libraries, including SDL, Allegro, SFML, FLTK, and Qt.
[src:raylib/opengl] A few libraries have been designed solely to produce an OpenGL-capable window.
[src:raylib/opengl] The first such library was OpenGL Utility Toolkit (GLUT), later superseded by freeglut.
[src:raylib/opengl] Given the high workload involved in identifying and loading OpenGL extensions, a few libraries have been designed which load all available extensions and functions automatically.
[src:raylib/opengl] Examples include OpenGL Easy Extension library (GLEE), OpenGL Extension Wrangler Library (GLEW) and glbinding.
[src:raylib/opengl] Extensions are also loaded automatically by most language bindings, such as Java OpenGL, PyOpenGL and WebGL.
[src:raylib/opengl] Mesa 3D is an open-source implementation of OpenGL.
[src:raylib/opengl] It can do pure software rendering, and it may also use hardware acceleration on BSD, Linux, and other platforms by taking advantage of the Direct Rendering Infrastructure.
[src:raylib/opengl] As of version 20.0, it implements version 4.6 of the OpenGL standard.
[src:raylib/opengl] In the 1980s, developing software that could function with a wide range of graphics hardware was a challenge without a cross-platform library.
[src:raylib/opengl] Software developers wrote custom interfaces and drivers for each piece of hardware.
[src:raylib/opengl] This was expensive and resulted in multiplication of effort.
[src:raylib/opengl] By the early 1990s, Silicon Graphics (SGI) was a leader in 3D graphics for workstations.
[src:raylib/opengl] Their IRIS GL API became the industry standard, as IRIS GL was considered easier to use, and it supported immediate mode rendering, therefore being faster than competitors like PHIGS.
[src:raylib/opengl] SGI's competitors (including Sun Microsystems, Hewlett-Packard and IBM) were also able to bring to market 3D hardware supported by extensions made to the PHIGS standard, which pressured SGI to open source a version of IRIS GL as a public standard called **OpenGL**.
[src:raylib/opengl] However, SGI had many customers for whom the change from IRIS GL to OpenGL would demand significant investment.
[src:raylib/opengl] Moreover, IRIS GL had API functions that were irrelevant to 3D graphics.
[src:raylib/opengl] For example, it included a windowing, keyboard and mouse API, in part because it was developed before the X Window System and Sun's NeWS.
[src:raylib/opengl] IRIS GL libraries were heavily tied into SGI's proprietary graphics hardware and could not be open sourced as-is due to hardware patents and trade secrets.
[src:raylib/opengl] These factors required SGI to continue to support the advanced and proprietary Iris Inventor and Iris Performer programming APIs while market support for OpenGL matured.
[src:raylib/opengl] One of the restrictions of IRIS GL was that it only provided access to features supported by the underlying hardware.
[src:raylib/opengl] If the graphics hardware did not support a feature natively, then the application could not use it.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL overcame this problem by providing software implementations of features unsupported by hardware, allowing applications to use advanced graphics on relatively low-powered systems.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL standardized access to hardware, pushed the development responsibility of hardware interface programs (device drivers) to hardware manufacturers, and delegated windowing functions to the underlying operating system.
[src:raylib/opengl] With so many different kinds of graphics hardware, getting them all to speak the same language in this way had a remarkable impact by giving software developers a higher-level platform for 3D-software development.
[src:raylib/opengl] In 1992, SGI led the creation of the OpenGL Architecture Review Board (OpenGL ARB), the group of companies that would maintain and expand the OpenGL specification in the future.
[src:raylib/opengl] Two years later, they also played with the idea of releasing something called "OpenGL++" which included elements such as a scene-graph API (presumably based on their Performer technology).
[src:raylib/opengl] The specification was circulated among a few interested parties – but never turned into a product.
[src:raylib/opengl] Released in 1996, Microsoft's Direct3D eventually became the main competitor of OpenGL.
[src:raylib/opengl] Over 50 game developers signed an open letter to Microsoft, released on June 12, 1997, calling on the company to actively support OpenGL.
[src:raylib/opengl] On December 17, 1997, Microsoft and SGI initiated the Fahrenheit project, which was a joint effort with the goal of unifying the OpenGL and Direct3D interfaces (and adding a scene-graph API too).
[src:raylib/opengl] In 1998, Hewlett-Packard joined the project.
[src:raylib/opengl] It initially showed some promise of bringing order to the world of interactive 3D computer graphics APIs, but on account of financial constraints at SGI, strategic reasons at Microsoft, and a general lack of industry support, it was abandoned in 1999.
[src:raylib/opengl] In July 2006, the OpenGL Architecture Review Board voted to transfer control of the OpenGL API standard to the Khronos Group.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL was the standard for many CAD software (such as Blender) and games in the 1990s and 2000s, and faces wide support across virtually all hardware vendors.
[src:raylib/opengl] Despite the emergence of newer graphics APIs like its successor Vulkan or Metal, OpenGL continues to be a widely used standard.
[src:raylib/opengl] This continued relevance is supported by several factors: ongoing development with new extensions and driver optimizations, its cross-platform compatibility, and the availability of compatibility layers like ANGLE and Zink.
[src:raylib/opengl] These layers allow OpenGL to run efficiently on top of Vulkan and Metal, offering a pathway for continued use or gradual transitions for developers.
[src:raylib/opengl] However, the graphics API landscape has been shifting, where some companies are moving away from OpenGL.
[src:raylib/opengl] In June 2018, Apple deprecated OpenGL APIs on all of their platforms (iOS, macOS and tvOS), encouraging developers to use their proprietary Metal API, which was introduced in 2014.
[src:raylib/opengl] Game developers have also begun to adopt newer APIs. id Software, who has been using OpenGL in their games since the late 1990s in games such as GLQuake or some games of the Doom franchise, transitioned away to its successor Vulkan in its id Tech 7 engine in 2016.
[src:raylib/opengl] They first supported Vulkan in an update for their id Tech 6 engine.
[src:raylib/opengl] The company's first licensed use of OpenGL was in its Quake II engine, also known as id Tech 2.
[src:raylib/opengl] In March 2023, Valve removed OpenGL support from Dota 2 in favor of Vulkan.
[src:raylib/opengl] Atypical Games, with support from Samsung, updated their game engine to use Vulkan, rather than OpenGL, across all non-Apple platforms.
[src:raylib/opengl] The Khronos Group, the consortium responsible for OpenGL's development, has stopped updating OpenGL, with the last release made in 2017.
[src:raylib/opengl] It has not received a number of modern graphics technologies, such as hardware accelerated Ray Tracing, on-GPU video decoding, and advanced anti-aliasing algorithms like Nvidia DLSS and AMD FSR.
[src:raylib/opengl] Another modern feature, Mesh Shaders, was initially only supported through an Nvidia exclusive extension, however in 2025, a cross-vendor OpenGL Mesh Shader extension was released.
[src:raylib/opengl] Google's Fuchsia OS, while using Vulkan natively and requiring a Vulkan-conformant GPU, still intends to support OpenGL on top of Vulkan via the ANGLE translation layer.
[src:raylib/opengl] The first version of OpenGL, version 1.0, was released on June 30, 1992, by Mark Segal and Kurt Akeley.
[src:raylib/opengl] Since then, OpenGL has occasionally been extended by releasing a new version of the specification.
[src:raylib/opengl] Such releases define a baseline set of features which all conforming graphics cards must support, and against which new extensions can more easily be written.
[src:raylib/opengl] Each new version of OpenGL tends to incorporate several extensions which have widespread support among graphics-card vendors, although the details of those extensions may be changed.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL 2.0 was originally conceived by 3Dlabs to address concerns that OpenGL was stagnating and lacked a strong direction.
[src:raylib/opengl] 3Dlabs proposed a number of major additions to the standard.
[src:raylib/opengl] Most of these were, at the time, rejected by the ARB or otherwise never came to fruition in the form that 3Dlabs proposed.
[src:raylib/opengl] However, their proposal for a C-style shading language was eventually completed, resulting in the current formulation of the OpenGL Shading Language (GLSL or GLslang).
[src:raylib/opengl] Like the assembly-like shading languages it was replacing, it allowed replacing the fixed-function vertex and fragment pipe with shaders, though this time written in a C-like high-level language.
[src:raylib/opengl] The design of GLSL was notable for making relatively few concessions to the limits of the hardware then available.
[src:raylib/opengl] This harked back to the earlier tradition of OpenGL setting an ambitious, forward-looking target for 3D accelerators rather than merely tracking the state of currently available hardware.
[src:raylib/opengl] The final OpenGL 2.0 specification includes support for GLSL 1.10.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL 2.1 adds support for Pixel Buffer Objects, sRGB textures and GLSL 1.20.
[src:raylib/opengl] Before the release of OpenGL 3.0, the new revision had the codename Longs Peak.
[src:raylib/opengl] At the time of its original announcement, Longs Peak was presented as the first major API revision in OpenGL's lifetime.
[src:raylib/opengl] It consisted of an overhaul to the way that OpenGL works, calling for fundamental changes to the API.
[src:raylib/opengl] The draft introduced a change to object management.
[src:raylib/opengl] The GL 2.1 object model was built upon the state-based design of OpenGL.
[src:raylib/opengl] That is, to modify an object or to use it, one needs to bind the object to the state system, then make modifications to the state or perform function calls that use the bound object.
[src:raylib/opengl] Because of OpenGL's use of a state system, objects must be mutable.
[src:raylib/opengl] That is, the basic structure of an object can change at any time, even if the rendering pipeline is asynchronously using that object.
[src:raylib/opengl] A texture object can be redefined from 2D to 3D.
[src:raylib/opengl] This requires any OpenGL implementations to add a degree of complexity to internal object management.
[src:raylib/opengl] Under the Longs Peak API, object creation would become atomic, using templates to define the properties of an object which would be created with one function call.
[src:raylib/opengl] The object could then be used immediately across multiple threads.
[src:raylib/opengl] Objects would also be immutable; however, they could have their contents changed and updated.
[src:raylib/opengl] For example, a texture could change its image, but its size and format could not be changed.
[src:raylib/opengl] To support backwards compatibility, the old state based API would still be available, but no new functionality would be exposed via the old API in later versions of OpenGL.
[src:raylib/opengl] This would have allowed legacy code bases, such as the majority of CAD products, to continue to run while other software could be written against or ported to the new API.
[src:raylib/opengl] Longs Peak was initially due to be finalized in September 2007 under the name OpenGL 3.0, but the Khronos Group announced on October 30 that it had run into several issues that it wished to address before releasing the specification.
[src:raylib/opengl] As a result, the spec was delayed, and the Khronos Group went into a media blackout until the release of the final OpenGL 3.0 spec.
[src:raylib/opengl] The final specification proved far less revolutionary than the Longs Peak proposal.
[src:raylib/opengl] Instead of removing all immediate mode and fixed functionality (non-shader mode), the spec included them as deprecated features.
[src:raylib/opengl] The proposed object model was not included, and no plans have been announced to include it in any future revisions.
[src:raylib/opengl] As a result, the API remained largely the same with a few existing extensions being promoted to core functionality.
[src:raylib/opengl] Among some developer groups this decision caused something of an uproar, with many developers professing that they would switch to DirectX in protest.
[src:raylib/opengl] Most complaints revolved around the lack of communication by Khronos to the development community and multiple features being discarded that were viewed favorably by many.
[src:raylib/opengl] Other frustrations included the requirement of DirectX 10 level hardware to use OpenGL 3.0 and the absence of geometry shaders and instanced rendering as core features.
[src:raylib/opengl] Other sources reported that the community reaction was not quite as severe as originally presented, with many vendors showing support for the update.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 introduced a deprecation mechanism to simplify future revisions of the API.
[src:raylib/opengl] Certain features, marked as deprecated, could be completely disabled by requesting a *forward-compatible context* from the windowing system.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 features could still be accessed alongside these deprecated features, however, by requesting a *full context*.
[src:raylib/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 8 Series and newer, ATI Radeon HD 2000 series and newer, Intel HD Graphics in Intel Sandy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL 3.1 fully removed all of the features which were deprecated in version 3.0, with the exception of wide lines.
[src:raylib/opengl] From this version onwards, it's not possible to access new features using a *full context*, or to access deprecated features using a *forward-compatible context*.
[src:raylib/opengl] An exception to the former rule is made if the implementation supports the ARB_compatibility extension, but this is not guaranteed.
[src:raylib/opengl] Hardware support: Mesa supports ARM Panfrost with Version 21.0.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 further built on the deprecation mechanisms introduced by OpenGL 3.0, by dividing the specification into a *core profile* and *compatibility profile*.
[src:raylib/opengl] Compatibility contexts include the previously removed fixed-function APIs, equivalent to the ARB_compatibility extension released alongside OpenGL 3.1, while core contexts do not.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 also included an upgrade to GLSL version 1.50.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL 3.3 includes minor additions, with the goal of retaining as much functionality as possible from OpenGL 4.0, while keeping support for older hardware.
[src:raylib/opengl] Additions include new blending functions, Sampler Objects and new texture and vertex formats.
[src:raylib/opengl] Support is also added for GLSL version 3.30, major and minor versions now match with OpenGL.
[src:raylib/opengl] OpenGL 4.0 was released alongside version 3.3.
[src:raylib/opengl] It was designed for hardware able to support Direct3D 11.
[src:raylib/opengl] As in OpenGL 3.0, this version of OpenGL contains a high number of fairly inconsequential extensions, designed to thoroughly expose the abilities of Direct3D 11-class hardware, such as tessellation.
[src:raylib/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Ivy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:raylib/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge and newer).
[src:raylib/opengl] Additionally, this is the last core profile supported by Apple macOS.
[src:raylib/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), and Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:raylib/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:raylib/opengl] (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge without stencil texturing, Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:raylib/opengl] VIRGL Emulation for virtual machines supports 4.3+ with Mesa 20.
[src:raylib/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1.
[src:raylib/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1, and Tegra X1.
[src:raylib/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 7000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel Skylake and newer, Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:raylib/opengl] Apple deprecated OpenGL in iOS 12 and macOS 10.14 Mojave in favor of Metal, but it is still available as of macOS 15 Sequoia (including on Apple silicon devices).
[src:raylib/opengl] The latest version supported for OpenGL is 4.1 from 2011.
[src:raylib/opengl] A proprietary library from Molten – authors of MoltenVK – called MoltenGL, can translate OpenGL calls to Metal.
[src:raylib/opengl] There are several projects that attempt to implement OpenGL on top of Vulkan.
[src:raylib/opengl] The Vulkan backend for Google's ANGLE achieved OpenGL ES 3.1 conformance in July 2020.
[src:raylib/opengl] The Mesa3D project also includes such a driver, called *Zink*.
[src:raylib/opengl] Microsoft's Windows 11 on Arm added support for OpenGL 3.3 via GLon12, an open source OpenGL implementation on top DirectX 12 via Mesa Gallium.
[src:raylib/opengl] Vulkan, formerly named the "Next Generation OpenGL Initiative" (glNext), is a ground-up redesign effort to unify OpenGL and OpenGL ES into one common API that will not be backwards compatible with existing OpenGL versions.
[src:raylib/opengl] The initial version of Vulkan API was released on February 16, 2016.
[src:raylib/raylib] The library is designed to be suited for prototyping, tooling, graphical applications, embedded systems, and education.
[src:raylib/raylib] The source code is written in the C programming language (specifically using C99), which is distributed under a zlib/libpng OSI certified open-source license.
[src:raylib/raylib] It supports compilation to several target platforms, including Windows, Linux, macOS, FreeBSD, Android, Raspberry Pi and HTML5.
[src:raylib/raylib] raylib has been ported to more than 70 programming languages in the form of bindings, but many of these ports are not stable.
[src:raylib/raylib] raylib development began in August 2013 when Ramon Santamaria created the library to support a game development course aimed at students with artistic backgrounds and no prior coding experience.
[src:raylib/raylib] Student feedback throughout the course shaped its early development, and by mid-2014 the library was being showcased at game development events in Barcelona.
[src:raylib/raylib] raylib 1.0 was released in November 2013, offering basic functionality for window management, 2D/3D rendering, texture and font loading, and audio playback.
[src:raylib/raylib] Eight minor releases over the following five years added Android, WebAssembly, and Raspberry Pi support, multiple OpenGL backends, VR support, shaders, a physics module, and an expanding examples library.
[src:raylib/raylib] raylib 2.0 was released in July 2018, coinciding with Santamaria leaving his professorship to focus on raylib full-time.
[src:raylib/raylib] All external dependencies were removed, OpenAL was replaced by the miniaudio library, and continuous integration support was introduced.
[src:raylib/raylib] A subsequent minor release, raylib 2.5, added Unicode text rendering, skeletal animation with glTF support, and a redesigned gamepad system.
[src:raylib/raylib] raylib 3.0 was released in April 2020, refactoring the codebase to improve portability and language binding support.
[src:raylib/raylib] Global state was consolidated into context structures, and all file I/O was centralized to allow custom virtual filesystem integration.
[src:raylib/raylib] Bindings for over 40 programming languages were available by this point.
[src:raylib/raylib] A minor update, raylib 3.5, followed in December 2020, adding Raspberry Pi 4 native mode and improved software rendering aimed at embedded devices.
[src:raylib/raylib] raylib 4.0 was released in November 2021, focusing on API consistency through broad renaming and documentation improvements.
[src:raylib/raylib] It introduced an experimental input recording and replay system, optional user-controlled game-loop timing, and OpenGL 4.3 support, with rlgl and raymath promoted to usable standalone libraries.
[src:raylib/raylib] raylib 5.0 was released in November 2023 to mark the library's 10th anniversary.
[src:raylib/raylib] Its most significant change was splitting the core platform module into separate, swappable backends, making new platform support far more approachable, with SDL2 added as an alternative desktop backend alongside an unofficial Nintendo Switch backend.
[src:raylib/raylib] Spline drawing, a new pseudo-random number generator, and a redesigned automation events system were also introduced.
[src:raylib/raylib] A minor release, raylib 5.5, followed in November 2024, adding RGFW and SDL3 as additional platform backends, GPU skinning support for 3D model animations.
[src:raylib/raylib] A software renderer backend was introduced, allowing raylib to run entirely on CPU without a GPU.
[src:raylib/raylib] New platform backends were added for Win32 and Emscripten without third-party library dependencies, alongside a headless memory framebuffer mode.
[src:raylib/raylib] Fullscreen and High-DPI scaling were completely redesigned, and the skeletal animation system was rebuilt to support blending between animations.
[src:raylib/raylib] The examples collection grew past 215 entries, and a dedicated examples management tool was introduced to streamline contributions.
[src:raylib/raylib] This is a simple example that creates a window with text, given on the GitHub page of Raylib.
[src:raylib/raylib] As of April 2026, GitHub lists around 2500 projects matching the `raylib` topic.
[src:raylib/raylib] raylib consists of several modules that are exposed to the programmer through the API.
[src:raylib/raylib] raylib has bindings for more than 70 different programming languages, created by various language communities.
[src:raylib/raylib] Computer programming languages that are updated to the latest version include: C#, Crystal, D (Dlang), Fortran, Go, Jai, Java, Lua, Nim, Python, Rust, V (Vlang), and Zig.
[src:raylib/raylib] There is also a C++ wrapper for users of C++ who prefer a less C-like, more C++-idiomatic usage, and also can be imported as a C++ module.
[src:raylib/raylib] A list of bindings is available in the BINDINGS.md file in the raylib GitHub repository.
